<TEXT>
the capital of liberia resembles a 
ghost town few people venture into the streets that soldiers loyal 
to president samuel doe rule with the ferocity of men painted into 
a corner 
you just halt when i give you an order a sergeant screamed 
at a passing car saturday pointing his m16 automatic rifle 
straight at the driver 
the car screeched to a halt you a rebel or something the 
sergeant asked with nervous irritation his finger trembling on the 
trigger 
one group of soldiers pounced on a civilian tied his hands 
behind his back and bundled him into a waiting truck he had been 
recognized by one of the soldiers his compatriots said the 
man was savagely beaten but the look on his face showed he didnt 
know why 
the soldiers wearing shabby uniforms were redeyed from lack 
of sleep and heavy drinking many soldiers have sneaked away from 
this rebelencircled capital in civilian clothes hoping to escape 
the final carnage 
but some are caught at rebel roadblocks the rebels look for 
soldiers posing as civilians by checking their shins for marks left 
by army boots 
youths most of them members of does krahn tribe are being 
taken off the streets to be given emergency military training 
as other government soldiers put it 
that means they are issued rifles and ammunition and sent back 
into the street to keep order 
only troops manning their checkpoints in groups of three or four 
are visible along monrovias straight avenues 
at many points cars stand jacked up on bricks their wheels 
missing 
most of monrovias 500000 inhabitants are crowded into their 
houses they strain for a look at what is going on but few wander 
into the open here and there an army patrol fires a volley into 
the air largely to reassure itself 
in street after street all the shops and churches are 
shuttered the windows of many shops are smashed a sign of 
looting government offices are open but empty the staff absent 
doe is barricaded into the executive mansion guarded by an 
elite unit of about 500 soldiers rebels were reported on sunday to 
have advanced to a mile away 
civilians tried to demonstrate for peace a month ago and troops 
opened fire to disperse the crowd 
now people seem to lack the will to take a stand 
everyone is afraid said leonine steward a secretary 
its as though all of us were playing russian roulette with each 
other we dont know who gets the bullet 
the downtown spriggs payne airport is heavily guarded by 
government troops the air charter manager peter seebok recently 
turned away dozens of wouldbe refugees for lack of space 
promising to be back for more the next day but when the next day 
came there were no passengers waiting the troops had taken over 
little if any food has been coming in to the city which is 
also without water electricity and telephone service 
men women and children had been carrying home buckets and 
plastic containers of water from polluted streams now they are no 
longer allowed to go out for water 
all we can do is hope for rain to collect some of it for our 
daily needs said a man employed by an international bank that is 
not functioning 
but our only real hope is for the president to decide to go 
as long as he stays theres no hope for him or for us he said 
about 400000 of liberias 25 million people lived in monrovia 
before the 7monthold insurgency closed in on the capital forcing 
an exodus to the countryside and abroad 
at a private zoo in the city the man who runs it is afraid 
hungry monrovians will try to eat his collection of african 
antelopes called duikers 
swiss taxidermist charles steiner who runs the zoo as a hobby 
gets a small subsidy from the swiss embassy and from private 
companies to feed the animals and keep them from starving to death 
the duikers are crowded into a series of small cages on the edge 
of a swamp a white cross on a red shield tells passersby that 
steiner and his animals are under swiss protection 
the trouble is everyone is very hungry he says god knows 
how long i can save my animals from being eaten 
the great masonic temple located nearby on top of a hill is an 
empty shell its windows are barred and elephant grass grows in its 
onceelegant yard government policy had been made in the building 
before 1980 when liberia was run by the descendants of freed 
american slaves who founded the country in 1847 
the americanliberians called for no apparent reason the 
congo tribe had run the country like european colonialists 
but their rule ended on april 12 1980 when 18 krahn 
noncommissioned officers of the presidential guard stormed the 
executive mansion they killed president william r tolbert and 
divided the cabinet posts among themselves 
but life in the city continued pretty much as usual 
this time its different 
</TEXT>
