human rights group said 
their trial was a travesty of justice there was no 
convincing evidence to justify their conviction and details of the 
charges were withheld from the defendants throughout the trial 
amnesty said in a statement 
the two men were among 10 people arrested in feburary and tried 
on charges of subversion and showing contempt for president paul 
biya amnesty said 
it said yondo and ekane were imprisoned and the others were 
given suspended prison sentences or acquitted 
amnesty said the treatment of the men and the unfairness of 
their trial strongly suggests their arrests and convictions were 
politically motivated 
the defendants were illegally detained and held mostly 
incommunicado for several weeks after their arrests the statement 
said two of the men were reportedly tortured it said 
ekane said he had been stripped beaten and forced to remain 
standing without food or water for three days amnesty said 
one of the laywers defending the men was killed by police on the 
last day of the trial and other lawyers received death threats or 
threats against their practices the human rights group said 
the trial itself was described as kafkaesque defendants 
were not given details of the charges they faced and were denied 
time to confer with lawyers or prepare a defense it said 
documents used as evidence against them included two drafts of 
an appeal for signatures in support of political change and a draft 
article for publication by an exiled opposition group amnesty said 
there was no evidence that the documents advocated overthrow of 
the government or that they had been published or distributed the 
statement noted 
amnesty said both the imprisoned men suffer serious health 
problems it said they have little prospect of regular visits from 
relatives who could bring them food and medicine 
amnesty believes the men have been imprisoned solely for their 
nonviolent political activities and are prisoners of conscience 
