<TEXT>
here is a brief description of the eight 
remaining justices of the supreme court 
william rehnquist 65 appointed to the court in 1971 by 
president richard nixon and appointed chief justice by president 
ronald reagan in 1986 once a frequent dissenter he now is 
generally acknowledged as the leader of the courts working 
conservative majority rehnquist is well liked by his colleagues 
who praise him for his informal genial style 
byron r white 73 appointed to the court in 1962 by president 
john kennedy white generally votes with the conservatives 
although his deference to federal power can produce some 
contrasting results he voted with the liberals last month to 
uphold a key federal affirmative action program he is among the 
courts most avid questioners of lawyers during oral arguments and 
can be abrasive 
thurgood marshall 82 appointed to the court in 1967 by 
president lyndon johnson brennans most consistent ally marshall 
is the only black ever named to the court and is a figure of 
historic importance in the civil rights movement but critics say 
his interest in court work has flagged in recent years marshall 
has been an outspoken critic of reagan and has vowed to remain on 
the court as long as he is alive 
harry a blackmun 81 appointed to the court in 1970 by nixon 
he is best known as the author of the 1973 ruling in roe vs wade 
that established a womans constitutional right to an abortion 
once labeled a conservative twin of former chief justice warren 
e burger he has cast generally liberal votes in recent years 
john paul stevens 70 appointed to the court in 1975 by 
president gerald ford he is a maverick whose intellectual 
brilliance has been overshadowed by his independence he generally 
votes with the liberals but is unpredictable he was with the 
dissenters who voted to uphold laws against flag burning stevens 
is known for his bow tie and his incisive and unfailingly polite 
questioning of lawyers at oral arguments 
sandra day oconnor 60 appointed to the court in 1981 by 
reagan the only woman ever to be a justice she has controlled the 
balance of power until now on abortion issues she also has been a 
swing vote on affirmative action oconnor is generally 
conservative but has provided some key liberal votes particularly 
on issues affecting womens rights she is hardworking and not 
given to broad pronouncements or sweeping rulings she underwent a 
mastectomy last year and says her cancer has been cured 
antonin scalia 54 appointed to the court in 1986 by reagan a 
scholar and jurist of unquestioned brilliance he has tried to pull 
the court further to the right and has been outspoken in 
criticizing conservative colleagues who prefer incremental change 
scalia has a libertarian streak and strict adherence to 
constitutional principles that occasionally produce a surprise he 
cast a recent dissenting vote when the court refused to grant child 
abuse suspects the right to confront their young accusers in court 
anthony m kennedy 53 appointed to the court in 1988 by 
reagan the courts newest member solidified a conservative 
majority but says he has felt no special pressure in being a 
pivotal figure an unassuming californian he was reagans third 
choice for a vacancy created by the retirement of centrist justice 
lewis f powell kennedys major defections from the conservative 
camp were his votes to strike down laws against flag burning 
</TEXT>
