<TEXT>
having shown once again that its 535 members 
are vulnerable to the same greed and lust that inflict the populace 
that elected it congress now is proceeding to discipline two of 
its own 
the house is considering a reprimand for rep barney frank 
dmass its ethics committee found that frank fixed parking tickets 
for a homosexual male prostitute whom he had hired as a personal 
aide with his own money and gave misleading information about him 
to authorities a house vote is expected this week 
the senate ethics committee proposes denouncement of sen 
dave durenberger rminn for breaking rules on outside income 
evading disclosure requirements and improperly accepting free 
limousine rides senate action is expected within a couple of weeks 
despite the different words reprimand and denouncement 
theres no significant difference between the two chambers 
punishments like almost everything else in congress a large and 
murky vocabulary has evolved to hide the unpleasant choices at hand 
when a member of congress misbehaves house or senate there are 
only three real options do nothing scold the offender or throw 
him or her out 
doing nothing is a popular option for example republican rep 
donald e lukens has been convicted in his home state of ohio for 
having sex with an underage girl the house has not disciplined him 
reprimand and denouncement fall in the middle category 
in each case the chamber approves a document that then gets 
attached to the offender like a scarlet bullseye to be used in 
the next election by his or her opponent 
given the impact on their public images lawmakers are very 
sensitive to the wording of such statements 
durenbergers aides argue to reporters that a denouncement 
is something less than a censure which is the term most 
commonly used in past senate cases it isnt 
in the house though censure is a small halfstep up from 
reprimand the difference being that the offender must actually 
attend and stand in the well of the house and hear the speaker 
recite the punishment 
tears ran down the face of rep dan crane rill when he was 
brought before his colleagues after being censured in the sex 
scandal involving a teenage congressional page he lost his bid for 
reelection 
both chambers are extremely reluctant to expel a member usually 
reserving that punishment for the voters to dish out 
thats already happened with lukens as hes been defeated in 
the ohio primary and it happened in the general election two years 
ago with rep fernand st germain dri the former banking 
committee chairman who was investigated but never charged by the 
ethics committee 
but if the voters want a tainted lawmaker they can have him 
and in some cases they have 
rep gerry studds dmass and rep edward roybal dcalif 
are examples of house members who have retained their house seats 
and considerable power despite being punished studds was censured 
for sex with a male page and roybal was reprimanded for his part in 
an influencepeddling scandal 
its been more than a decade since the house expelled a member 
and the senate is even more reluctant to expel than the house it 
hasnt done so in this century 
it also seems less necessary in the senate 
no senator has been reelected after being censured and though 
the formal punishment may seem light to an outsider the effect 
within the clubby institution is severe 
much more so than the house the senate functions via personal 
relationships and mutual trust earned over the years a censured 
senator becomes a pariah 
one senior senate aide recalled when former sen thomas dodd 
father of the current sen christopher dodd dconn was censured 
for financial misconduct more than two decades ago 
asked how a member of the club could be so punished by his 
colleagues he responded yes we have a club in the senate and 
when a senator misbehaves we eat him 
in dodds day it was a private dinner now with the advent of 
cspan millions of people will watch in their homes as congress 
tries to judge its own 
