<TEXT>
prime minister lothar de maziere has averted 
the collapse of his broad coalition government with an agreement by 
the governing parties to put off a decision on the precise date of 
german unification 
the social democrats east germanys secondlargest party and 
the smaller liberal centrist alliance had threatened to pull out of 
the government over the issue but reached a compromise on sunday 
the parties have demanded that unity occur a day before 
elections set for dec 2 in that way all of germany not two 
separate nations would vote at once 
but de maizieres christian democrats have said unity before the 
vote would place east germans under a government they did not elect 
the west german government if only for a day 
the coalition partners agreed to have the two german governments 
consult on the issue and try to come up with a solution 
lawmakers did resolve a major difference in the election laws of 
the two germanys by establishing the same 5 percent minimum for 
party representation as exists in west germany 
the law means parties must get at least 5 percent of the vote in 
state and local elections to win seats in councils or legislatures 
the communists successor party the party of democratic 
socialism had pressed for a 3 percent threshold 
de maiziere and his christian democrat allies in west germany 
led by chancellor helmut kohl have favored allowing east germans 
to hold elections for a united parliament on the same day as in the 
west but counting the vote separately in areas that are now part 
of east germany 
this would lower the amount of votes east german parties would 
need for representation in the federal parliament allowing smaller 
parties a chance to get past the 5 percent threshold and win seats 
it would also help the christian democrats who rely more on 
coalitions with smaller parties than the social democrats form a 
legislative majority 
also sunday parliament voted to reconstitute the countrys five 
states that had been dissolved under communist rule 38 years ago 
the move was intended to facilitate east germanys merger with the 
west under terms of bonns constitution 
lawmakers overwhelmingly voted to make oct 14 the date for 
elections in the states of mecklenburg saxony saxonyanhalt 
thueringia and brandenburg as well as in east berlin 
the move restores the five states to roughly their 1946 borders 
and abolishes the 14 districts created by the communists in a 1952 
administrative reform program 
the parliament also passed its last independent budget the 
388 billion budget will have a deficit of about 206 billion 
which will be covered in part by the bonn government and through 
new credit 
east germany merged its economy with west germany on july 1 
experts have predicted that up to half its 8 million workers could 
lose their jobs as formerly statesupported industries lose to free 
market competition 
