now on the party should be united and organize itself as an 
opposition confronting likud 
peres and rabin then briefly shook hands 
peres who has been party chief since 1977 said later that he 
would not seek revenge 
there is room for everyone for yitzhak rabin and others he 
said on an interview on israel radio 
although rabin and peres both appealed for party unity 
observers predicted that labor will remain split and unable to 
present a strong opposition 
we will see two organized and hostile camps with leaders who 
hardly speak with each other a kind of prolonged war of 
attrition said israel radios political observer hanan cristal 
likud may forget about opposition it will have an easy life in 
the government 
mordechai gur a senior labor member and a rabin supporter said 
peres victory had weakened the party 
we thought we should change the leadership to lead a strong 
active opposition with peres it would be very difficult we shall 
do our best but im afraid it would not be as strong as it could 
have been gur said 
recent polls have consistantly indicated that rabin 68 is 
israels most popular leader 
also a former prime minister he gained popularity for his tough 
