<TEXT>
some scientists suspect the measuring 
instruments made and used by a connecticut company to create the 
hubble space telescopes two mirrors were faulty or improperly 
used a newspaper reported 
the hartford courant said several scientists familiar with the 
hubble project are focusing on the optical devices used to guide 
the grinding and polishing of the mirrors as the root of the 
focusing problems 
because of the mirror problem the 15 billion orbiting 
observatory cannot properly focus the light from distant stars as 
it orbits 380 miles above the earth about half of its astronomical 
research must be delayed until a solution is found 
the mirrors a 945inch primary mirror and a 125inch 
secondary mirror were made by perkinelmer corp at its danbury 
division which it sold last year to hughes aircraft co 
hughes danbury optical systems inc officials agree there is a 
problem with one mirror but are not convinced the company is 
responsible said hughes spokesman thomas j arconti 
from day one people have been attempting to lay blame 
arconti said that is just much too early 
the instruments which are called null correctors also were 
used to test the finished mirrors on the hubble 
daniel schulte of lockheeds palo alto calif research labs a 
member of a nasa committee assigned to find ways to correct the 
hubbles focusing problem told the newspaper he is certain there 
was something wrong with a null corrector 
schulte said other committee members support his theory the 
courant said other scientists who spoke on condition of anonymity 
also agreed the problem was in the null correctors 
the national aeronautics and space administration and other 
scientists believe the hubbles flaw is most likely in the larger 
mirror 
schulte said he has ruled out the possibility of a problem with 
the design of the null corrector for the primary mirror and 
concluded the problem had to be in the manufacture or assembly of 
the null corrector 
if the null corrector is correct the mirror would be 
correct said daniel schroeder a nasa telescope scientist who 
helped oversee the hubble project and is chairman of the physics 
and astronomy department at beloit college in wisconsin 
abe offner a retired scientist who designed the null system in 
the 1970s for perkinelmer said it was almost certain the null 
corrector was flawed 
offner is among several scientists due to meet wednesday and 
thursday in danbury with a sixmember nasa team investigating the 
hubbles flaw there are other possibilities to explain problems 
with the telescope but they are kind of farfetched he said 
investigators have not yet tested the null correctors the 
newspaper said 
