<TEXT>
officials in mongola began tabulating results 
today of the first multiparty elections ever held in the worlds 
secondoldest communist state after the soviet union 
voters turned out across the asian nations 600000 square miles 
of grasslands and steppe on sunday for a primary involving 2400 
candidates for the national legislature or great peoples hural 
the balloting was to reduce the field to 860 candidates two for 
every seat in the hural the runoff is scheduled for next sunday 
a source in the capital ulan bator visited 10 polling stations 
in the city and described the voting as very well organized 
the voters appeared to have a lot of confidence in the voting 
they seemed enthusiastic about having a choice this time said 
the source who spoke on condition of anonymity 
he said results would be announced at a news conference tonight 
sundays elections made mongolia the latest sovietbloc nation 
to move toward multiparty democracy following a huge outpouring of 
prodemocracy sentiment during street demonstrations last winter 
mongolians were given the choice of voting for candidates from 
the ruling communist party known as the mongolian peoples 
revolutionary party or from one of five new opposition parties 
the opposition parties were formed following weeks of rallies 
for reform that forced former president and communist party chief 
jambyn batmonh from power last spring 
the communists known as the mongolian peoples revolutionary 
party and the opposition parties all say their next step will be 
marketstyle economic reforms 
only 300 of the candidates in the primary are members of the 
noncommunist parties together they have 15000 members compared 
with the communist partys 90000 
the ruling party is almost certain to win a majority in the 
430seat great peoples hural because one seat is being allocated 
for every 2000 rural residents compared with one seat per 10000 
urban residents 
most of the support for the noncommunist parties is among 
educated urban residents but the communists remain strong in rural 
areas 
the opposition parties however hope to win a strong majority 
in the 53seat small hural which was newly created to replace the 
current standing committee of the great peoples hural 
the small hural will meet yearround and hold most governmental 
power however the great hural still will elect a new president 
the incumbent punsalmaagiin ochirbat was elected by the outgoing 
great hural in april 
the small hural originally was to have been elected by the great 
hural but under pressure from the opposition the government 
agreed to allocate small hural seats according to the percentage of 
votes each party receives 
the communists made more concessions last month after the 
opposition parties threatened to pull out of the election 
the ruling party agreed to allow opposition participation in 
local election commissions which count ballots and to allow 
international observers to monitor the election the communists 
also gave each party state funds for campaigning and suspended 
party cells in the army and state security forces during the 
campaign and balloting 
foreign observers in ulan bator include a team of british 
parliamentarians 
mongolia has been ruled by the communists since 1921 when a 
small band of revolutionaries aided by soviet troops drove out the 
chinese who had controlled mongolia since 1691 china retained 
southern mongolia called inner mongolia where mongolian tribal 
princes had formed alliances with the chinese 
</TEXT>
