a chess expert drawing inspiration from sherlock 
holmes and lewis carroll said today he believes he has cracked a 
puzzle that could lead to the whereabouts of a woman missing since 
january 
police believe the woman is buried somewhere in ireland and the 
chess experts work would appear to reinforce these views 
detective superintendent roy fletcher of lancashire police said 
the puzzle drawn by a man arrested in connection with the case 
is a crude map and a series of moves for a black king a black 
queen a black pawn and white king all pawns 
raymond keene chess correspondent of the times of london and an 
international grand master said the puzzles author shows 
tremendous intellectual arrogance allied with a perverted 
ingenuity and rooted in the belief that he can dangle all sorts of 
intellectual clues in front of the polices nose without their 
being able to solve them 
fletcher said therese terry 43 has been missing since january 
colin english was arrested in june and charged with fraud in 
relation to funds taken from mrs terrys bank account 
while in custody he drew a map which he says gives the answer 
to where she is buried fletcher said he claims she died at 
her own hand 
keene who was given the puzzle friday said he was unable to 
pin down the burial site but it is my firm belief that the body 
is located some miles northwest of limerick 
keene wrote in todays times that the diagram was a crude mirror 
image of southern ireland rotated 90 degrees to put east at the 
bottom and that roman numerals stood for various places in england 
and ireland 
he believes the black king is the suspect the black queen is 
the victim the black pawn is the suspects brother and the white 
pawns are the police a scarcely veiled insult to the suspects 
assessment of the competence of the police force 
keene wrote that the moves appear to show events between jan 
18 when mrs terry left lancashire for london and jan 23 when 
english returned from ireland 
keene said that while trying to solve the puzzle he recalled a 
sherlock holmes story called the dancing men in which sir 
arthur conan doyles fictional detective breaks a code that used 
figures of dancing stick men 
he also was inspired by lewis carrolls story in which alice 
