<TEXT>
the navy began its needleinahaystack search 
of the ocean floor today for a cargo door that blew off a united 
airlines jumbo jet and caused nine people to be swept to their 
death over the pacific 17 months ago 
investigators hope the door will help them establish beyond 
doubt the cause of the accident 
during the weeklong search a deepsea probe equipped with sonar 
and a video camera will be dragged across a 24squaremile area 
about 100 miles southwest of honolulu 
if the door is spotted another device will be used at a later 
date to recover it 
after their ship arrived at the scene overnight workers this 
morning began setting up a transponder field an electronic grid 
used to mark locations during the sophisticated undersea probe 
said lt cmdr bob anderson a spokesman for the pacific fleet 
flight 811 was bound for new zealand on feb 24 1989 with 355 
people aboard when the door tore popped off at 22000 feet 
carrying away a section of fuselage and causing sudden 
decompression of the boeing 747 nine people were sucked out five 
others were seriously hurt the crew managed to return the jet to 
honolulu 
the national transportation safety board concluded that a 
deficiency in the design of the doors locking mechanism probably 
indicated to the pilot that the door was locked when it was not 
the agency blamed united the boeing co and the federal aviation 
administration for failure to correct problems with the door 
ntsb investigators said the door still could provide evidence 
for improving aircraft safety the agency asked the navy to find it 
the door is believed to be 15000 feet down 
its like a needle in a haystack but a big factor is what the 
bottom looks like said project manager bob whaley 
whaley said the ocean floor in the search area is generally 
flat which is good for searching 
the cost of the project will not be known until it is completed 
anderson said 
a search for the door was to have begun last october but was 
delayed by technical problems during testing of the orion deep 
submergence search system he said 
the 226foot navy ocean tug narragansett left pearl harbor on 
sunday and arrived on the scene about midnight the underwater 
portion of the search system known as a towfish is attached to 
the tug by a 35000foot triplearmored cable 
the towfish is operated from on board the vessel a computer 
enhances its sonar findings for later analysis anderson said 
the orion system has been used once before to retrieve an 
airplane that crashed off the east coast earlier this year 
anderson said 
the search will be carried out by the navys prime contractor 
for underwater search operations the naval sea systems command and 
steadfast search division of oceaneering international inc 
anderson said 
oceaneering international helped find wreckage from an airindia 
jumbo jet that was ripped apart by a bomb over the atlantic in 
1985 and parts of a south african jumbo jet that burst into flames 
and crashed off east africa in 1987 
it made an unsuccessful attempt to recover vital parts from the 
korean air lines 747 shot down by the soviet union in 1983 and 
helped in the search for the space shuttle challenger in 1986 
anderson said 
</TEXT>
