the bush administration said today it has 
approved prototypes of six foreignmade semiautomatic rifles 
redesigned to eliminate militarystyle features that resulted in 
their ban as imports last year 
however it was unclear if any requests to import the weapons 
have been submitted or approved said bureau of alcohol tobacco 
and firearms spokesman jack killorin 
receiving approval were new designs of the uzi ak47 galil 
hk91 sar8 and sar4800 officials said the washington post 
first reported the approvals in todays editions citing documents 
obtained by the firearms policy project under the freedom of 
information act 
those rifles were among the 43 styles of semiautomatic 
assaultstyle rifles banned from import by the administration last 
july the weapons had such characteristics as threaded barrels to 
accommodate a silencer flash suppressors that could hide the 
shooters position at night and prevent a loss of night vision 
provisions for mounting a bayonet folding or collapsible stocks 
pistol grips and large capacity magazines 
an administration official speaking on condition that he not be 
identified said weapons of the type recently approved could be 
adapted by the purchaser to add the prohibited features he said 
such features would be prohibited by federal law under a crime bill 
now pending in congress 
earlier white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said 
apparently the way the existing rules are written atf the 
bureau of alcohol tobacco and firearms is not authorized to 
prevent these weapons from coming in 
the new crime bill im told does rectify this problem he 
said we look forward to signing that crime bill 
fitzwater said the guns should not be allowed into the country 
if they are the same weapon that was originally banned and that 
was a circumvention of the rule 
the white house spokesman made the statements in his daily 
questionandanswer session with reporters later he issued a 
statement admitting that he had made a mistake 
the crime bill which the administration proposed limits the 
number of rounds in detachable magazines fitzwater said 
however it will not influence the redesign of weapons within the 
configuration of traditional sporting rifles i was wrong to 
suggest that the new crime bill will influence redesigned weapons 
federal regulations require that imported rifles be suitable to 
sporting purposes and the administration determined that the 43 
styles many of which were favored by drug traffickers did not 
meet that requirement 
nine manufacturers of the banned weapons have provided the atf 
with plans or prototypes of new rifles that eliminate the 
militarystyle accoutrements and the atf has told six that the new 
styles meet the sporting requirement killorin said 
the bottom line is if the firearms conform to the changes 
required without bayonet slugs without flash suppressors night 
sites pistol grips and largecapacity detachable magazines then 
were talking about a weapon consistent with semiautomatic sporting 
weapons killorin said 
since such weapons fit the sporting requirement the atf must 
approve them he said 
the prototypes that were looking at are weapons that have 
none of the accoutrements not even the pistol grip he said 
a pistol grip that hangs down behind the trigger is intended to 
enable the shooter to have control while firing from the hip or to 
fire onehanded from the hip in a combat situation he noted 
although the new designs of the guns do not have such grips 
some are designed with a thumb hole in the stock a configuration 
frequently seen on olympicstyle rifles he said 
josh sugarman of the firearms policy project said the thumb hole 
serves as a pistol grip enabling weapons to be reloaded quickly 
and easily and fired from the hip 
in addition they can be easily modified to full 
assaultweapon configuration he said in a statement 
sugarman noted that the rifles still can accept largecapacity 
magazines even if they are fitted with limited capacity magazines 
something that is true of every firearm that takes a detachable 
magazine according to killorin 
although these weapons may look less threatening they are no 
less deadly sugarman said the industry knows this atf knows 
this and criminals know this 
killorin said the atf was still checking to see if there had 
been any requests to import the new weapons and whether such 
requests have been approved 
our correspondence has been relative to prototype 
configurations rather than a finished product he said 
the majority of our dialogue has been look if we made the 
following changes would this be importable for the most part 
weve said no youd have to change this and this 
