<TEXT>
ford motor co agreed monday to pay a 12 
million fine for repeatedly failing to keep track of onthejob 
injuries the government said 
in a separate settlement with the occupational safety and health 
administration ford agreed to launch a program to reduce ergonomic 
hazards or workplace injuries caused by repetitivemotion tasks 
at 96 percent of its plants 
the labor department called that agreement the most extensive 
ergonomics settlement in oshas history a ford spokesman said 
about 150000 workers would be affected 
the 12 million fine involves record keeping violations that 
osha inspectors found in 1989 when they visited a ford electronics 
and refrigeration facility in lansdale pa 
ford was misrecording or failing to record injuries that workers 
had received osha inspectors alleged 
the injuries involved cumulative trauma disorders or disorders 
of the musculoskeletal and nervous systems caused by repetitive 
motions such disorders are common occupational illnesses in the 
automotive industry where workers often have to repeat tasks on 
assembly lines 
ford spokesman dick routh attributed the poor record keeping to 
carelessness 
we had not put the effort into it that we should have 
certainly osha got our attention with the size of the fine he 
added 
osha originally hit ford with a 2 million fine because it was 
the third time the automaker had been cited for record keeping 
violations and ford had failed to live up to an earlier pledge of 
improving procedures the agency said 
as part of the record keeping agreement signed monday ford will 
establish at 12 of its facilities an audit system for keeping 
track of records involving workers medical compensation 
sickness accident and health insurance information 
the company will then cross check the records against an osha 
log and provide record keeping training if the error rate is 
greater than 5 percent either nationwide or at an individual 
facility 
on the ergonomic settlement ford has voluntarily agreed to 
implement a program to reduce workers risks of developing 
cumulative trauma disorders 
several businesses nationwide have taken voluntary steps to 
reduce those types of injuries as osha considers mandating 
ergonomic programs 
labor secretary elizabeth dole in announcing the ford 
agreement said the effort to reduce repetitivemotion injuries 
will be one of the greatest worker health and safety concerns in 
the next decade 
preventive measures include redesigning work stations such as 
adjusting workbench heights redesigning tools training workers 
and using mechanical or other devices to prevent excessive lifting 
fords ergonomic program which will involve analyses of various 
jobs and their risks will be partially administered by the united 
auto workers union which represents ford workers 
last year osha reached a similar ergonomics agreement with 
chrysler and the uaw to control cumulative trauma disorders in five 
chrysler auto assembly plants 
the ford program will include a medical management program to 
provide for early identification of cumulative trauma disorders 
that would include periodic workplace walkthroughs by medical 
staff having workers fill out questionnaires every two years to 
gather information on symptoms of workrelated disorders and 
encouraging employees to report early signs of problems 
</TEXT>
