<TEXT>
motorists in seattle are burning the dirtiest 
gasoline according to a consumer survey released monday that also 
said chevron brands nationwide contain on average the most 
cancercausing benzene 
the survey found widely different levels of toxic aromatics 
especially benzene in gasoline depending on regions of the 
country premium gasoline sold in miami contained a third as much 
benzene as the same gasoline sold in seattle 
earl ross spokesman for the american petroleum institute said 
such variations werent unusual 
gasolines are blended differently for different parts of the 
country because of differences in driving conditions climate 
altitude and seasonal changes he said 
benzene and other socalled aromatic additives which are 
used to boost gasoline octane are highly toxic and can cause 
cancer studies have indicated cleanair legislation before 
congress would require significant reductions in the use of those 
additives by refiners 
health specialists are concerned primarily about exposure to the 
toxic vapors during refueling although the petroleum industry has 
said such exposure is at such low levels that it does not warrant a 
health concern 
the environmental protection agency has estimated that there are 
about eight chances in 100000 of a person developing cancer from 
selfservice refueling of motor vehicles over a lifetime the epa 
said the risk is greater for those who live near or work at 
gasoline stations terminals or refineries 
the survey of gasoline sold in 18 metropolitan areas was 
produced by citizen action a washingtonbased consumer and 
environmental group and was based on fuel samples tested annually 
by the motor vehicle manufacturers association 
the american petroleum institute accused citizen action of 
misusing data to present an unduly alarmist picture of the 
health risks to motorists 
the citizens action study showed that premium gasoline sold in 
the west generally contained higher levels of aromatics including 
benzene an exception appeared to be atlanta where the level of 
benzene in premium gasoline 29 percent was second only to 
seattle 3 percent 
shell premium gasoline sold in atlanta had the highest benzene 
content of any gasoline tested or 54 percent shell in recent 
months has touted the benefits of clean gasoline when promoting its 
reformulated premium su2000e brand 
but other gasoline brands in other cities also showed high 
levels of benzene exxons premium in los angeles and chevrons 
premium in san francisco contained more than 36 percent benzene 
this is gasoline at its dirtiest said edwin rothschild 
energy policy director for citizen action 
by comparison the average benzene content in gasoline is 
slightly more than 2 percent cleanair legislation in the final 
stages of being approved by congress calls for refiners to limit 
their benzene levels to less than 1 percent and overall aromatic 
levels to 25 percent 
the citizen action survey showed that some gasoline brands 
already meet the anticipated cleanair requirement 
in miami where average benzene levels in premium gasoline were 
only 1 percent mobils premium had a benzene level of onehalf of 
1 percent and three other brands union amoco and exxon all 
contained well below 1 percent benzene premium brands from exxon 
amoco and texaco had similar levels in dallas washington dc and 
denver 
obviously oil companies are capable of manufacturing premium 
unleaded gasoline with less than 08 percent benzene rothschild 
said at a news conference 
gasoline from the same company can have widely different levels 
of benzene depending on region and type of gas the survey showed 
for example while texaco sold premium gasoline with 067 percent 
benzene in denver its regular gasoline sold in boston had nearly 5 
percent benzene content 
rothschild said the controversial additives should be eliminated 
we are appalled that companies like chevron and shell have the 
audacity to tell the public that they sell quality gasoline when in 
many cities they are the purveyors of the most toxic gasoline on 
the market he said 
