<TEXT>
rival shiite moslem forces on monday 
reinforced their front lines around a strategic mountaintop town 
in southern lebanon as thousands of civilians took advantage of a 
lull in the fighting to flee 
police reported a marked decrease in fighting between fighters 
of the proiranian fundamentalist hezbollah or party of god and 
the syrianbacked amal militia 
the lull occurred as the battle between the rival shiite 
factions for control of the strategic town of jarjou and nearby 
villages close to israels selfdesignated security zone in 
southern lebanon entered its second week 
police said a syrian combatant was killed and two amal 
militiamen were wounded in daylong sporadic exchanges of artillery 
and sniper fire 
the dead fighter was identified by police as a syrian who 
belonged to the damascusbased arab baath socialist party about 
200 baathists and a symbolic force of the syrian social nationalist 
party have been fighting alongside the amal militia 
israeli jets made repeated reconnaissance flights monday over 
southern lebanon to monitor the shiite fighting police said 
mondays casualties raised the toll to 126 people killed and 369 
wounded since the shiite fighting broke out anew on july 16 
the fighting began when hezbollah attacked and seized jarjou 
from amal in an effort to expand its area of control toward the 
mediterranean and open up a badly needed sea route to iran its 
main supplier of arms 
it was the latest round of fighting in a 3yearold intermittent 
conflict between amal and hezbollah for mastery of the countrys 
12 million shiite moslems who make up lebanons largest sect 
at least 1167 people have been killed and 4011 wounded in the 
inconclusive power struggle by police count 
police said palestine liberation organization guerrillas 
stationed between the amal and hezbollah forces in the disputed 
region occupied four new hilltop positions west of jarjou on 
sunday 
the palestinian force is now capable of preventing any advance 
from either side against each other said lt col anwar madi 
commander of the plo intervention force as he inspected his 
positions around jarjou monday 
plo fighters mainly from yasser arafats fatah faction have 
been trying to stop the fighting between the two shiite groups 
apparently to halt the hezbollah advance toward sidon a southern 
port where palestinian guerrillas are based it is 10 miles 
northwest of jarjou 
amal and plo guerrillas fought a threeyear war in lebanon 
between 1985 and 1988 but have joined together in attacks aimed at 
driving the hezbollah forces out of jarjou 
police said amal rushed in 1000 more militiamen with dozens of 
truckloads of ammunition to its positions around jarjou over the 
weekend amal already had about 6500 frontline fighters in iqlim 
altuffah or the apple province where the fighting is raging 
hezbollah set up several additional artillery and mortar 
batteries in jarjou police said the fundamentalist group has 
fielded at least 2000 fighters in the province 
the reinforcements caused panic among the regions remaining 
25000 inhabitants who fear the fighting might intensify 
long lines of fleeing villagers trudged through the rugged 
hills carrying their household belongings under their arms and on 
their heads 
most of them sought refuge in southern lebanons major cities of 
sidon tyre and nabatiyeh others fled to open fields sleeping at 
night in cars 
</TEXT>
