<TEXT>
about 150000 people took part in a 
funeral procession monday to pay their respects to former bulgarian 
communist leader georgi dimitrov whose remains were removed from 
his mausoleum last week 
the remains of dimitrov revered as national hero during four 
decades of communist rule were cremated after being transferred 
from the mausoleum in downtown sofia 
both the opposition and some members of the ruling socialist 
party had called for removing dimitrovs remains and converting the 
mausoleum to other uses critics argue the mausoleum is a relic of 
the past out of step with the countrys recent push toward 
democracy 
the mostly elderly crowd many of whom had come from the 
countryside walked about three miles in the funeral procession 
from a square in front of alexander nevski cathedral to sofias 
central cemetery where a memorial ceremony was held 
the observances were organized by the socialists the reform 
party created from the old communist party 
as the funeral procession passed through the streets of the 
capital some young people on the sidewalks whistled in apparent 
disapproval no incidents were reported 
addressing the crowd at the funeral ceremony alexander lilov 
the socialist party leader appealed to party members to close 
their ranks on the way to radical renewal and reform 
lets transform the bulgarian socialist party into a model of 
a modern leftwing party lilov said 
lilov said the removal of dimitrovs remains and their burial at 
a public cemetery did not represent any major historical revision 
regarding the countrys first communist leader the state bta news 
agency reported 
he is still considered a political figure of enormous national 
and international prestige but he was not faultless and 
made some mistakes lilov said 
also attending the ceremony were other senior socialist party 
officials including premier andrei lukanov and former president 
petar mladenov who resigned earlier this month 
the urn with dimitrovs ashes will be buried in a family grave 
in a private ceremony for relatives later this week a bta official 
said 
a leading figure in the international communist movement 
dimitrov was acquitted in a trial in late 1933 in which he was 
charged with complicity in the fire that destroyed the german 
reichstag parliament building 
historians say that the arson was a nazi provocation 
in 1946 dimitrov became leader of the bulgarian communist party 
and also headed the government until his death in 1949 
during his leadership the noncommunist opposition parties were 
either disbanded or merged in a communistdominated mass 
organization 
the disinterment of dimitrov marks another step away from four 
decades of orthodox communist rule since the ouster of communist 
leader todor zhivkov in november 
despite longtime official veneration dimitrov has become 
increasingly unpopular particularly in sofia where the 
noncommunist opposition union of democratic forces emerged as the 
winner in last months multiparty elections the socialists won a 
majority in the parliament due to a strong showing in the 
countryside and provincial cities 
a commission appointed by sofias municipal council will propose 
possible new uses for the former mausoleum a massive stone 
building constructed in one week after dimitrovs death 
in the past the mausoleum was a major attraction in sofia much 
like lenins tomb in moscow 
the mausoleum was guarded around the clock by two soldiers in 
traditional balkanstyle dress uniform equipped with 
bayonettopped rifles 
</TEXT>
