<TEXT>
amnesty international on monday welcomed an 
announcement by cameroon president paul biya that all political 
prisoners in his central african country would be released soon 
but the human rights group noted cameroon continues to imprison 
people for their political beliefs 
no exact date was announced for the release 
in a statement amnesty noted biyas government frequently holds 
people in administrative detention without charge or trial tries 
them unfairly before military tribunals or keeps them in jail after 
they have been acquitted or completed their prison terms 
abdoulaye mazou for example was convicted in 1984 to a 
fiveyear term for his involvement in an unsuccessful coup attempt 
the londonbased group said 
the former lawyer and magistrate was considered a prisoner of 
conscience when he was held in administrative detention for a year 
after he had completed his sentence even after his release in 
april mazou has been confined to his home amnesty said 
the nobel peace prizewinning group noted many of the more than 
100 political prisoners held since 1984 in connection with the 
attempted coup remain in detention despite the presidents promise 
in april that they would be released 
among those held are former transport company official paul 
daissala dakole and habouba mousse an airline employee 
former president ahmadou ahidjo turned over power to biya in 
1982 after 22 years in power though the transfer came about 
peacefully the two men later had a fallingout 
on april 6 1984 a faction of the elite republican guard loyal 
to ahidjo tried to topple biya fighting raged around yaounde for 
two days before the rebels were suppressed by loyal troops 
official estimates say 70 died but observers said as many as 
1000 were killed at least 46 of the arrested plotters were later 
executed 
ahidjo who was in retirement in france was tried in absentia 
and condemned to death biya later lifted the sentence 
amnesty noted that despite biyas statements on the release of 
political prisoners two men recently were jailed after trying to 
set up a political party in the oneparty state 
former bar association president yondo mandengue black and 
anicet ekane a company director were sentenced to 3 and 4year 
prison terms in april by a special military court the rights group 
said 
the two were imprisoned for attending meetings to discuss 
multiparty democracy and setting up a new political party 
amnesty on monday called for the release of the men they said 
were prisoners of conscience 
two others nicole ngakou and her brother george yopa were 
acquitted on charges of distributing subversive material in 1987 
but continue to be held in administrative detention without charge 
or trial 
the amnesty statement also cited the case of djeukam tchameni 
dominique who was sentenced by a military court earlier this year 
to three years in prison for bringing into the country an 
audiocassette containing criticism of the government 
amnesty said it welcomed biyas statement that he was ready to 
allow the group to visit cameroon and meet with government 
officials 
