<TEXT>
borisav jovic the serb now leading 
yugoslavias collective presidency said on monday that individual 
states will be allowed to secede from the fragile yugoslav 
federation 
the federation of six member states may itself be radically 
reshaped 
four republics are in favor of federation two are for a 
confederation jovic said in a statement read to reporters after 
his meeting with slovenias president milan kucan in ljubljana the 
republics capital 
the local governments of croatia and slovenia insist that this 
balkan nation of 23 million residents should become a loose 
association of nearindependent states which would remain united 
only if joint interests warrant it 
communistruled serbia the largest republic has held until now 
that a confederate structure would be too unstable and advocated 
retaining the federal system installed in 1945 the three small 
remaining states bosnia and hercegovin macedonia and montenegro 
also prefer a federation 
jovic said that if states favoring a looser union could not 
reach agreement with the rest of the country they would be 
permitted to enter into a confederation with the other republics 
that would stay in the current federal structure 
a subvariant is that regions that so desire would also be 
allowed to secede from yugoslavia jovic said 
he said he and kucan had very detailed and very open talks on 
the future of yugoslavia and its future constitutional setup 
we agreed that everybody should refrain from making any 
unilateral changes until a joint decision on the future of this 
ethnically diverse nation is reached jovic said 
slovenias newly elected government has served notice the 
northern republic of 2 million people would declare itself 
independent if the other states do not accept its demands to turn 
yugoslavia into a grouping of sovereign republics 
croatias new centerright authorities also support 
transforming yugoslavia into a confederation but say they want to 
discuss the nations future makeup at a joint meeting of the 
legitimate representatives of all states 
the slovenian parliament last week publicly refused to consider 
a letter from the federal presidency because it was not written in 
the local language 
slovenia will seek sovereignty complete economic and cultural 
sovereignty in a yugoslav confederation kucan said in his 
statement 
yugoslavia was formed as a joint kingdom of serbs croats and 
slovenes after world war i occupied and dismembered by nazi 
germany in 1941 it reemerging as a communiststyle federation 
under josip tito after world war ii with macedonia montenegro and 
bosniahercegovina added to the three prewar states 
serbia only now is taking a tentative step toward a multiparty 
system 
slovenia and croatia held free elections this year in which 
centerright parties won the majority marking the first free 
balloting here in 50 years 
