<TEXT>
nearly half of all puerto ricans 
favor statehood over the caribbean islands current commonwealth 
status and only 8 percent want independence according to a poll 
published monday 
although support for statehood appears to be growing the poll 
found that it still falls short of the majority required by bills 
now before congress to change puerto ricos political relationship 
with the united states 
the survey of 1204 eligible voters indicated that if puerto 
rico held a plebiscite on its status now 483 percent would choose 
statehood 406 percent commonwealth status and 8 percent 
independence with the remainder undecided 
the poll was published monday by san juans el mundo newspaper 
a previous poll published by the newspaper el nuevo dia in 
february showed 43 percent favoring statehood 36 percent 
commonwealth status 5 percent independence with the remainder 
undecided or refusing to reveal their preference 
however the two polls were conducted by different 
organizations which did not necessarily use the same methods 
the senate and the house are considering separate bills 
authorizing a plebiscite on puerto ricos status in june 1991 
both bills would allow puerto ricans to choose whether they want 
the island to become the 51st us state keep the commonwealth 
relationship but with increased autonomy or break away to form an 
independent nation 
the senate version would put the results of the plebiscite into 
immediate effect the house version would require negotiations with 
congress over implementation of the islanders choice 
gov rafael hernandez colon leader of the procommonwealth 
popular democratic party proposed a status plebiscite in his 1989 
inaugural speech following his reelection to a second consecutive 
fouryear term 
under the 38year commonwealth arrangement puerto ricos 33 
million residents are us citizens but they pay no federal taxes 
and cannot vote for president 
statehood supporters contend that the commonwealth status is a 
form of colonialism that makes puerto ricans secondclass citizens 
commonwealth supporters say the current status allows puerto 
ricans to enjoy the benefits of citizenship without giving up their 
spanish cultural identity 
fear of economic collapse has stymied the independence movement 
the el mundo poll found that 435 percent of puerto ricans would 
migrate to the us mainland if the island became independent 
the poll was carried out for el mundo and the educational 
station wmtjtv by the us firm frank i luntz amp associates based 
in arlington va and had a margin of error of 28 percent 
findings were based on facetoface interviews with randomly 
selected eligible voters from june 23 to july 2 
</TEXT>
