maoist shining path guerrillas killed 20 
militiamen in attacks on two andean towns police said monday 
there were no reports of rebel casualties in the fighting 
police said the clashes took place july 17 in jaujin and chichipon 
near the maranon river 210 miles north of lima 
police did not arrive in the isolated towns until july 20 the 
bodies of the militiamen had been left unburied and were badly 
decomposed according to police 
police gave the following description of the attacks 
about 30 rebels killed 17 of the militiamen in a long firefight 
in jaujin after earlier killing three soldiers in an attack on 
chichipon 
the rebels were armed with assault rifles and machine guns while 
the militiamen had a few old rifles but were armed mainly with 
sticks and machetes 
drug traffickers are active in the area around chichipon and 
jaujin police said the shining path often provides protection for 
drug traffickers in return for arms and money 
the peruvian army has established militia groups throughout 
mountain and jungle regions to allow villages to defend themselves 
from rebels 
the government says more than 19000 people have died in 
political violence since the shining path took up arms 10 years ago 
the shining path following the tactics of chinas mao tsetung 
is conducting a prolonged guerrilla campaign in the countryside and 
aiming eventually at surrounding and strangling perus coastal 
cities 
