general said it is hard to classify souters judicial philosophy 
whether its liberal or conservative its not the issue in 
his mind the issue in his mind is what was intended in the 
constitution tiffany said 
souter a state trial judge for five years before serving on the 
new hampshire supreme court until last april 30 appears to have 
had two political patrons warren rudman and john sununu 
rudman is a moderate republican senator from new hampshire who 
as state attorney general hired souter sununu a former governor 
who elevated souter to the state supreme court is the conservative 
white house chief of staff 
rudman once said souter who was considered a potential supreme 
court nominee by the reagan administration before anthony m 
kennedys appointment in 1988 possesses the most brilliant legal 
mind he had ever encountered 
souter has been serving as a judge on the bostonbased 1st us 
circuit court for less than three months 
in state cases 
he was the lone dissenter in a 1985 state supreme court 
decision that struck down the use of police sobriety checkpoints 
the nations highest court upheld such police tactics earlier this 
year 
he was part of a 32 majority in a 1986 decision that allowed 
the main owner of the seabrook nuclear plant to sell bonds needed 
to complete the longentangled project his court rejected appeals 
from the state consumer advocate and several antiseabrook groups 
in one of the few civil rights cases in which souter 
participated he joined the state supreme courts ruling in 1987 
that said homosexuals may be barred from becoming adoptive or 
foster parents but the state court said in that decision that 
homosexuals may not be barred from running daycare centers 
as a state judge in 1983 he held a 345 am hearing at the 
request of thengov sununu and ordered state employes staging a 
sickout over pay issues back to work under threat of 
5000aday fines against their union 
people for the american way a liberal group said its review of 
souters state supreme court record indicates he interprets 
constitutional guarantees narrowly especially in criminal cases 
the organization criticized him for an opinion that overturned a 
sexual assault conviction souter held that the defendant should 
have been allowed to present testimony that the victim behaved in a 
sexually provocative manner toward several men in a tavern the 
group said 
