<DOCNO> AP900723-0173 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a summary of developments in the news industry for the week of 
july 1623 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the associated press is accelerating 
implementation of its photostream network and installation of ap 
leaf picture desks aiming to finish nationwide by the end of 1991 
a year earlier than previously announced 
president louis d boccardi said july 19 that the decision to 
step up the schedule came in response to encouragement from member 
newspapers to put the new photo system in place as soon as possible 
installations of photostream and ap leaf picture desks will 
start in september in new york the state in which ap will save the 
most money by switching from landline transmission to satellite 
delivery of pictures 
installations will start in october in other northeastern 
states in february installations will commence simultaneously in 
the three other divisions of the aps domestic photo service 
southeast central and west 
within each region ap teams will work in more than one state at 
a time but the general order for installations is determined by 
where the greatest savings can be made to help pay for the program 
the original timetable had called for a 28month installation 
program but development of hardware and software has proceeded 
at a pace that indicates we should attempt to accomplish this 
enormous task in 16 months boccardi said 
he said the ap would give its members at least a quarterly 
update on the progress of the installation program 
in addition to the landline savings the northeastern region is 
the first to begin conversion because of its proximity to aps 
photo and computer headquarters in new york aps technical center 
in new jersey and leaf systems inc in massachusetts which 
manufactures the ap leaf picture desk 
the new york region states in order of installations are new 
york pennsylvania massachusetts rhode island new jersey maine 
vermont new hampshire and connecticut 
installation in the other three regions will be in this general 
order 
central texas ohio indiana kentucky michigan iowa 
nebraska south dakota north dakota minnesota illinois kansas 
missouri wisconsin arkansas oklahoma colorado and wyoming 
west california nevada oregon washington arizona new 
mexico idaho montana utah alaska and hawaii 
southeast louisiana mississippi tennessee alabama georgia 
florida north carolina west virginia virginia south carolina 
maryland and delaware 
additional photo editors will be hired for the control bureaus 
of each region to edit and transmit pictures from bureaus and 
newspapers in the states under their jurisdiction additional staff 
also will be hired to install the darkrooms and train member 
newspaper staffs ap will set up a fulltime help desk to assist 
members with the changeover 
black and white pictures currently are transmitted in about nine 
minutes and color in 30 minutes when fully implemented 
photostream will allow delivery of black and white pictures in one 
minute and color in three minutes 
the ap also announced it would use the ap leaf picture desk for 
its internal photo computer system and would discontinue 
development and marketing of the ap vax picture desk which runs on 
digital equipment corp computers 
the ap leaf picture desk exceeds our expectations in power 
speed and functionality said john reid ap vice president and 
director of communications and technology work on new features 
is proceeding rapidly members attending anpatec saw the 
difference and demonstrated an overwhelming preference for the 
leaf 
if an ap member newspaper does not want an ap leaf picture desk 
it may keep its present photo receiver or accept a twominute 
receiver or it may choose to buy an electronic darkroom from 
another company in which case ap will provide a rebate of 47 
weekly for five years effective on the date the member would have 
received its ap leaf picture desk 
the present photo receiver will be left in place at sites where 
an ap leaf picture desk is installed 
members receiving an ap leaf picture desk and photostream will 
be assessed a surcharge of between 15 and 80 weekly depending on 
circulation 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a newspaper cannot be held liable for 
breaking a promise of confidentiality to a source the minnesota 
supreme court ruled in rejecting a 700000 award against the 
states two biggest daily papers 
lawyers for both sides agreed the 42 ruling july 20 has 
farreaching implications for the nations news organizations 
the court rejected a jurys award of 200000 in compensatory 
damages and 500000 in punitive damages to dan cohen 
cohen had sued the saint paul pioneer press and the star tribune 
of minneapolis for 1982 stories identifying him as the source of 
documents showing a democratic candidate for lieutenant governor 
had been convicted of shoplifting 12 years earlier 
cohen then a republican gubernatorial candidates consultant 
had given the newspapers reporters the information in return for 
assurances of confidentiality but the newspapers editors 
overruled the reporters believing readers should know the 
information came from the gop candidates campaign 
the supreme court upheld an appeals courts dismissal of cohens 
claim of fraudulent misrepresentation but reversed the appeals 
courts ruling allowing him to claim breach of contract 
to impose a contract theory on this arrangement puts an 
unwarranted legal rigidity on a special ethical relationship 
precluding necessary consideration of factors underlying that 
ethical relationship associate justice john simonett wrote 
the court also said enforcement of the promise of 
confidentiality under a doctrine that implies a legal contract 
where none exists would violate the newspapers first amendment 
rights 
cohens lawyer elliot rothenberg said he would appeal to the 
us supreme court 
the associated press filed the only friendofthecourt brief in 
the case cohens victory at trial had produced a spate of similar 
lawsuits around the country the aps attorneys said 
the breachofcontract theory was being used by plaintiffs 
elsewhere to avoid the constitutional obstacles that stand in the 
way of winning privacy and libel suits said dick winfield an 
attorney for the ap 
the minnesota ruling is the first definitive opinion by a 
state supreme court directly addressing the issue and the media 
can take considerable comfort in the case he said 
joel r kramer executive editor of the star tribune said his 
paper was especially pleased that the court has ruled that the 
decision to publish true facts relating to the activities of a 
political source in a political campaign is one that is protected 
by the first amendment 
but bill salisbury the pioneer press reporter who accepted 
cohens documents and objected strongly to his editors decision to 
identify cohen as the source said the ruling will make his job 
more difficult 
what the ruling tells reporters is that if an editor wants 
to overrule your promise of anonymity to a source he or she can do 
so salisbury said so it will make me much more careful about 
granting confidentialtiy to sources and it will make me much more 
reluctant to reveal the names of my sources to editors 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

