<TEXT>
the boston globe filed the first legal challenge 
to the states new tax package july 19 claiming it is 
unconstitutional to tax the materials used to publish a newspaper 
the tax package which became law a day earlier not only 
broadens the 5 percent sales tax to hundreds of business services 
it also extends the tax to the materials and equipment used to 
publish a newspaper or transmit a broadcast 
the globes suit in supreme judicial court did not raise the 
issue of broadcasters instead the globe argued massachusetts law 
exempts manufacturers from paying a sales tax on raw materials and 
tools used in production and thus it would be discriminatory to 
apply such a tax to newspaper companies 
newspaper publishers are the only manufacturers of tangible 
personal property excluded from the manufacturing exemptions the 
lawsuit said 
the globe also argued the tax law opens the possibility of 
burdensome taxation on the press that could obstruct critical 
comment about the government 
robert mehrman head of the massachusetts broadcasters 
association said he could not discuss whether radio and television 
stations also would file suit against the tax 
the globes suit pointed to a similar tax that was enacted in 
minnesota and struck down in 1983 by the us supreme court 
minnesota taxed the ink and paper used by publishers while other 
businesses using those products were not subject to the tax the 
supreme court said differential taxation of the press ran 
counter to the rights guaranteed by the first amendment and said 
the state did not show a compelling reason to permit the tax 
</TEXT>
