west virginians can join the war on 
drugs by using coupons to send tips to authorities under a 
statewide program that is an offshoot of a campaign by the 
williamson daily news 
in announcing the program july 16 state police hailed it as a 
new wave in citizen crimefighting but civil libertarians warned 
that the program under which tips can be mailed or phoned in 
anonymously will create a society in which people spy on each 
other 
the program was adapted from one used by the daily news 
authorities received nearly 700 replies after the paper printed 
coupons on its own and invited people to mail them to state police 
federal state and local authorities arrested 46 people in mingo 
county as a result of the coupon tips in june wally warden editor 
of the newspaper said six people had been convicted so far 
the daily news got the idea from the clinton iowa herald 
which asked readers to anonymously list the names of anyone they 
suspect of using or selling drugs the milford conn citizen also 
has run a similar campaign 
warden said his paper had been contacted by law enforcement 
agencies in florida illinois iowa kansas kentucky ohio 
oklahoma tennessee and texas for information about the program 
