<DOCNO> AP900723-0177 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a proposed uniform libel law under which courts 
would decide whether statements are true or false before 
determining appropriate damages would not guarantee first amendment 
rights for defendants critics say 
the uniform defamation act is the first proposal for a 
nationwide standard in libel disputes it was discussed july 20 by 
the national conference of commissioners on uniform state laws a 
group appointed by the nations governors to draft model 
legislation 
the 28page draft outlines a twostage procedure for libel 
trials a court would first determine whether a statement under 
question was true or false only later during the trials second 
stage would a court decide what if any damages to assess 
safeguards for the press protection if a reporter acted 
without malice or allowances made if a plaintiff is a public 
official would not apply in the trials first stage 
the committee said the draft was based on the premise that 
plaintiffs are more interested in clearing their names than in 
receiving damages 
harvey perlman dean of the university of nebraskas college of 
law and author of the draft said the proposed laws intent was to 
protect plaintiffs reputations better but it also would benefit 
news organizations 
under the proposal news organizations could print retractions 
or pay a plaintiffs legal fees after the first stage a provision 
proponents say would shorten trials and reduce the amount of 
damages awarded 
we wanted to create some incentives for the plaintiff to stop 
early perlman said 
but critics argue the committees desire to design safeguards 
for a persons reputation would create a chilling effect on the 
first amendment 
one of our central concerns is the committees desire to move 
the law in favor of the plaintiff said henry r kaufman counsel 
for the libel defense resource center there will be a chilling 
effect if the media believes it is going to face higher costs and 
greater burdens of libel and litigation 
others at the annual conference questioned creating one standard 
for an intricate field of first amendment law and court decisions 
i dont feel its an area of the law where you can provide a 
uniform act said john mcclaugherty a lawyer from charleston 
wva the first amendment is constantly being reinterpreted and 
by the time a law was passed it would already be out of date 
the earliest a proposal would be redrafted and returned to the 
350member conference would be next year perlman said but no date 
was set for a vote 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
maines highest court rejected a 
television stations attempt to withhold portions of a videotaped 
interview sought by a prosecutor as evidence in a criminal 
investigation 
officials of wcshtv declined to comment on the july 20 ruling 
saying they would meet with the stations lawyers to plan their 
next move 
in its unanimous decision the maine supreme judicial court 
dismissed the stations assertion that first amendment guarantees 
of a free press established a qualified privilege to protect 
the portions of the interview with biddeford police commissioner 
denis letellier that were not broadcast 
the justices said it was essential a york county grand jury view 
the full 12minute tape as part of its investigation into 
allegations that letellier used his position to get a motor vehicle 
charge against his son reduced 
after the tape was subpoenaed the station turned over the 2 
minutes of the interview that appeared on the air but withheld the 
unused portions 
the court based its ruling on a 1972 decision by a divided us 
supreme court that said a a proper balance must be struck on a 
casebycase basis between freedom of the press and the obligation 
of all citizens to provide relevant testimony about criminal 
conduct 
the public interest in the integrity of the biddeford police 
and city officials and in the effectiveness of the york county 
grand jury proceedings far outweighs any discernible impairment 
that the required production of the nonconfidential letellier 
videotape outtakes might conceivably cause to the first amendment 
interests asserted by wcsh chief justice vincent l mckusick 
wrote 
</TEXT>
