<TEXT>
when karen yee wanted to tell her 
uncles she was safe after a devastating earthquake she turned to 
the local radio station in baguio to get the message through 
when red cross official richard gordon needed to confer with 
authorities in quakedamaged cabanatuan he did so in a telephone 
patch provided by another radio station which broadcast the 
consultations live 
in the aftermath of the july 16 earthquake which left hundreds 
of people dead radio and television stations didnt only report 
the news they helped rescuers and worried relatives circumvent 
poor communications and served as a spur to a clumsy unresponsive 
bureaucracy 
broadcasters directed rescuers to areas of destruction relayed 
messages to family members separated by the disaster and solicited 
relief goods 
it was the radio stations which were coordinating rescue 
efforts broacasting the need for blood blankets medicines 
earthmoving equipment columnist luis beltran wrote in the 
manila standard government departments went to them for guidance 
on what to send where to send 
after the quake struck provincial affiliates of the major 
networks broadcast the first reports of destruction at that time 
president corazon aquinos staff said only that it was studying 
the extent of the disaster 
provincial officials unable to get through to manila by 
telephone broadcast appeals to the capital for assistance over 
private stations 
radio and television reporters traveled through the affected 
area and briefed government officials about which towns and cities 
were in urgent need of help 
they served as effective alternatives to government agencies 
whose addiction to routine has robbed them of the power of 
initiative and the ability to respond quickly former labor 
minister blas ople wrote in the manila bulletin 
as the extent of the disaster became clearer stations 
discontinued regular programming for roundtheclock quake coverage 
we shifted to publicservice priority programming because we 
feel that that is the need of the present time said maria 
asuncion lanuza program coordinator of dzbb i think we are 
complementing the government 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

