fears an orgy of democracy now that mikhail s gorbachev has 
loosened controls on the state broadcasting monopoly 
mikhail f nenashev the chief of gostelradio and a communist 
party traditionalist said in an interview broadcast on soviet tv 
that the change will make managing television much more 
complex than in the past 
the interview was broadcast july 16 the day after gorbachev 
issued his presidential decree on democratization of television 
and radio to cut back on the communist partys monopoly on the 
airwaves 
until now only groups approved by a state committee had access 
to soviet television as a result the communist party received 
large segments of time on the airwaves 
for a lasting time the television was under the party 
influence what we used to call and still call the party 
monopoly said nenashev who formerly was head of the state 
publishing committee 
now i am more afraid of an orgy of democracy rather than the 
party monopoly when the monopoly is replaced by numerous demands 
put forth by various groups parties various councils various 
organs he said 
hundreds of new groups have sprung up throughout the country in 
the last several years 
