<TEXT>
fcc officials staged surprise inspections at 
30 major market television and radio stations to check whether they 
are offering political candidates the lowest possible advertising 
rates 
the fcc held its firstever audits of broadcasters july 1617 
prompted by what an agency news release called an obligation to 
assure that broadcast stations are complying with political 
programming laws and rules especially in an election year 
the inspections carried out in five cities kicked off an 
auditing process that is expected to be completed before the fall 
congressional elections 
the audits were not the result of any complaint said milton 
graves chief of the fccs political division 
this is just a part of overseeing how the stations are 
complying he said we want to know what their practices are 
the fcc sent field inspectors to stations in cincinnati 
dallasfort worth philadelphia san francisco and portland ore 
in each city they visited four television stations an am radio 
station and an fm radio station 
under fcc regulations the lowest unit charge is available to 
political candidates 45 days before primary balloting and six days 
before a general election candidates may purchase single broadcast 
advertisements for the same price as commercial advertisers who buy 
a number of spots in the same time period 
the subject of political advertising rates has been a sore spot 
in congress where proposals are pending that would guarantee that 
candidates get the lowest rates without fear of being preempted by 
commercial advertisers who come in and offer to pay higher rates 
the stations audited were 
cincinnati wcpotv wkrctv wlwltv wiiitv wckyam and 
wwnkfm in cincinnati 
dallas kdfwtv kxastv wfaatv ktxatv krldam and kplxfm 
philadelphia kywtv wcautv wpvitv wgbstv wpenam and 
wwdbfm 
portland katutv kgwtv kointv kptvtv kwjjam and 
kksnfm 
san francisco kgotv krontv ktvutv kofytv knbram and 
kablfm 
</TEXT>
