<TEXT>
after three generations of uneasy coexistence 
with the communists in the kremlin the moslems of central asia are 
asserting themselves anew this is the second installment of a 
fourpart series based on an ap special correspondents journey 
through the soviet south 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a stonework galaxy of crescent moons 
has risen above the jagged outlines of tombs in the 1000yearold 
chigotai cemetery symbolically ending the long soviet eclipse of 
islam 
now communist party officials mourn their dead in the open 
instead of performing moslem rites secretly at home the aged 
guardian told visitors 
from ashkabad to alma ata across a 1200mile sweep of the 
soviet union central asians are embracing allah with the fervor of 
longlost prodigal sons 
on fridays row after row of barefoot bearded men in braided 
skullcaps chant centuriesold litanies and bow not toward moscow 
but to mecca 
koranic schools are filling with youngsters and countless 
mosques are reopening i cannot even say how many said 
mohammed zakhir deputy grand mufti of central asia but a new 
one opens every week it is endless 
religious leaders insist the new mood is joyous rather than 
militant a sign that tenacious faith has prevailed over an 
ideology that used propaganda and sometimes brute force to try to 
wipe it out 
this is no revival of islam because it was never dead said 
a tashkent professor who asked not to be quoted by name we 
always did in private what we can now do in public 
in fact many central asians say islam is an important force in 
the new political current carrying five of the soviet unions 15 
republics further away from moscow 
at the rural level power slipping away from local communist 
party officials is shifting to imams and in cities the party 
curries favor with the clergy 
an aggressive new attitude is evident in scattered outbreaks of 
violence 
in may in the crowded fergana valley east of this old uzbek 
capital witnesses said masked fundamentalist leaders led youths on 
a rampage of burning and looting in an apparent play for power 
three months earlier and farther south in dushanbe capital of 
mountainous tadzhikistan western visitors reported that moslem 
faithful went directly from praying to rioting and to demanding 
the resignation of local officials 
tashkent and the populous republic of uzbekistan are shared by 
nearly 100 ethnic groups with beliefs ranging from orthodox islam 
to marxist atheism in many areas they compete intensely for land 
housing and jobs 
mostly islam is a conduit for new feelings of identity for 
central asians it is as much a way of life as a religion the 
arbiter of family life community traditions and spiritual values 
from the first russian incursions to the south islam was a 
principal target and many soviet moslems say they feel a 
deepseated prejudice against russian people 
after the 1917 russian revolution moscow condemned islam as 
divisive superstition and sought to eliminate it along with other 
religions 
most mosques were closed and many were destroyed during some 
periods islam was banned outright more often it was vilified by 
intense propaganda and faithful moslems had to choose between 
allah and advancement in a partycontrolled society no muezzins 
wailed from minarets before prayer hardly a trickle of soviet 
moslems made it to mecca for the annual pilgrimage 
these past oppressions are ending said usmonhon alimov 
imam of the graceful albukhari mosque near samarkand among the 
few islamic holy sites to remain mostly unmolested since the 1920s 
young men are flocking to the faith openly and mosques are 
being established in every village he said 
today 55 million moslems most of them in central asia make up 
a fifth of the national population and every second child born in 
the soviet union is a moslem 
a decade ago during the height of ayatollah ruhollah khomeinis 
islamic revolution in neighboring iran powerful iranian radio 
transmitters urged moslem brothers to rise up against the soviet 
state at the time moscow was at war in afghanistan deploying 
some central asian soldiers against anticommunist moslem 
guerrillas 
today although moslem militancy seems to be growing political 
analysts see only limited outside meddling from across the iranian 
and afghan borders in soviet central asia fundamentalists are far 
outnumbered by more moderate moslems and shiites khomeinis 
branch of islam by sunni moslems 
but analysts say the potential for panislamic militancy is a 
serious cause for concern common values and even blood ties draw 
together populations separated for 70 years by an impenetrable 
border 
stanislav prozorov head of an islamic studies group in the 
soviet academy of sciences faults soviet leaders for misreading 
moslems ignoring them on one hand and overreacting on the other 
recently he told the daily paper komsomolets uzbekistana he saw 
a definite danger of an islamic explosion because of 
islamophobia on the part of soviet leaders and thinkers 
frustrated moslems might unite and respond with unpredictable 
vehemence he said had the kremlin understood islam in soviet 
asia it would never have invaded afghanistan he added 
western scholars agree michael rywkin of city college of new 
york has described growing masses that are practically 
unassimilable and indifferent to most official soviet values 
in march anatolii lukyanov chairman of the soviet national 
parliament met with the grand mufti of central asia mukhammad 
sadik mukhammad yusuf to discuss islamic affairs 
the 36yearold mufti was named chairman of the religious board 
of moslems of central asia last year after widespread complaints 
that his predecessor toadied to moscow 
in the meeting he assured soviet leaders he supported 
perestroika and was trying to help free captured soviet soldiers in 
afghanistan 
but in april on moscow television he sharply criticized the 
kremlin for interfering in islamic affairs and not giving moslem 
leaders the same access to the media as the russian orthodox 
hierarchy 
he said that because of ignorance of islam official policy 
tried to restrict the religion rather than take advantage of its 
ability to inspire social change and ethnic harmony 
episodes of zealotry should not raise fears that the fading 
soviet states will give way to harsh new islamic regimes central 
asian leaders say 
imam alimov blamed fanatics for trampling womens rights 
abusing nonmoslem settlers and frightening people whose ideas of 
islam were colored by fundamentalist excesses elsewhere 
these things are holdovers from the past the result of 
oppression he said people are learning again about islam 
young men are studying the koran these things will change 
</TEXT>
