<TEXT>
with some 41 million more foreigners expected to 
visit america this year its important for the business executive 
to know how to entertain them that can be complicated depending 
on where theyre from heres a guide to help you avoid cultural 
gaffes such as inadvertently inviting your guests to commit 
harakiri 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
look whos coming to dinner the big 
overseas client 
its decisionmaking time do you 
lock the dog in the basement 
order a dozen longstemmed red roses 
search through the gourmet shops for sheeps eyeballs sea 
slugs and freshfrozen bear paws 
greet the overseas visitor with a slap on the back a firm 
handshake perhaps three kisses on the cheek or will just two 
suffice 
see if the library has a recipe for stirfried bees 
dare do anything about sex after all in many parts of the 
world sex is regarded as a hospitable gesture a normal part of a 
business deal 
the outcome of your entire negotiations may depend on how you 
cope with a crosscultural crisis warns roger axtell a consultant 
and lecturer on worldwide business protocol 
after all trying to seduce a female client or a visiting wife 
is hardly getting things off to a crisp start which as axtell 
points out is what a dozen red roses connotes to a guest from west 
germany 
besides a bouquet of evennumbered flowers is considered bad 
luck in her country where etiquette further dictates that you 
remove the paper first 
make sure the paper is not white if the guest is japanese or the 
flowers purple if the recipient is from brazil or mexico these are 
the colors of death in those climes also white chrysanthemums in 
much of europe and flowers of any kind in kenya convey condolences 
further regarding gifts axtell recalls the curious case of a 
grand rapids mich furniture dealer who didnt know the foreign 
territory playing host at a dinner for buyers from japan he put a 
silver pocket knife as a gift at each place setting his guests 
left the gifts behind in silent dismay at what to them was an 
invitation to commit harakiri 
axtell spent 30 years as vice president of world marketing for 
parker pen co traveling in 80 countries observing and sometimes 
inadvertently committing some of the cultural gaffes that can 
result in an abrupt jagged line on the sales chart and the bosss 
cardiogram 
now a roving consultant on global business behavior axtell has 
just finished his third book the dos and taboos of hosting 
international visitors 
citing department of commerce figures axtell notes that some 41 
million international visitors will come to the united states this 
year and spend 50 billion just for travel food and accommodations 
for the first time there are more tourists arriving than 
departing a 15 billion balance of tourist trade is projected so 
its important that we welcome them by recognizing the differences 
in their cultures their way of having fun and doing business 
axtell warns that a host only invites disaster by attempting 
to duplicate any exotic foreign cuisine better to serve a 
typically american meal with due regard for religious dietary 
regulations but spare the corn on the cob its considered cattle 
food in many countries 
axtell urges a quick course in international body language as a 
basic survival tool in the global market place even a simple yes 
or no gesture can mean the opposite in other cultures 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900723-0196 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when a visitor from bulgaria or sri lanka nods his head that 
means no a head shake connotes yes a turk signifies no by 
raising his chin shutting his eyes and tilting the head 
backward 
ordinary gestures can convey extraordinary meanings to a foreign 
visitor advises axtell placing your hands on your hips is an 
aggressive gesture to a mexican forming a circle with the thumb 
and forefinger while elevating the other three fingers is a most 
obscene gesture in brazil 
similarly thumbs up is a rude gesture in bangladesh as is 
winking or beckoning with the middle finger in hong kong and 
malaysia 
the japanese he went on dislike being pounded on the 
back touching is unacceptable to them an open mouth is offensive 
so yawns belly laughs and chewing gum are out 
at table the differences can be perplexing a swede 
crisscrossing the utensils on his plate is asking for another 
helping and not signifying he is full among egyptians it is 
impolite to eat everything on the plate in finland it is bad luck 
to pass the salt hand to hand the shaker should be set down before 
the guest a japanese will accept a second helping only if asked 
twice zambians compliment the hostess by asking for seconds 
axtell regrets that toasting is a skill most americans never 
hone but at a dinner or banquet in less than a minute a 
wellcomposed toast can convey more elan and diplomacy than a month 
of slick talk 
unless you are an accomplished linguist axtell warns against 
attempting a toast in the visitors language he once tried 
memorizing the chinese words for thank you for a wonderful 
dinner i ate so much i must loosen my belt later he learned 
what he actually said was i ate so much the girth of my donkeys 
saddle is loose 
but his embarrassment was less than that of an iranian deputy 
oil minister who hoisted a glass at the petroleum club in houston 
with the toast as they say in your country up your bottoms 
but as jimmy carter found out on his 1977 trip to poland using 
an interpreter can sometimes double the trouble 
his interpreter made the arrival speech unforgettable even today 
in warsaw with the translation the president says he is pleased 
to be here in poland grasping your secret parts 
finally there is the question of sex while hosting a foreign 
client is one obliged to arrange for some group interaction in a 
hot tub an allpurpose escort service or a visit to a local 
pleasure palace 
while in other countries sex often is an expected part of 
business entertainment axtell answers not once in over 30 
years of hosting scores of business visitors from all over the 
world did one of them request or show any expectation for a hired 
sexual partner 
