<DOCNO> AP900723-0200 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
in a monumental undertaking the guthrie 
theater celebrates shakespeares history plays this summer with 
stirring sweeping productions of richard ii henry iv 
parts 1 and 2 and henry v 
they are not only monumental pieces of theater but major acting 
and logistical challenges for the regional theater which was 
founded in 1963 by tyrone guthrie 
the three productions with the two parts of henry iv 
combined into one play are being performed in repertory through 
sept 2 with a special encore week of performances oct 913 they 
employ two directors the theaters entire 28member acting company 
and a trio of distinctive settings by design wizard douglas stein 
the effort pays off handsomely its an amazing theatrical 
journey through more than 50 years of english history what makes 
it special is the chance to see these plays together to follow the 
arc of this history from the doomed reign of the foolish foppish 
richard ii to the monarchy of the charismatic henry v who rallies 
his nation to military victory over france 
these works are linked by many of the same characters watch 
bolingbroke turn into a troubled henry iv or the hedonistic prince 
hal grow into an impressive henry v and they reverberate with 
ideas that echo from play to play to play 
among other things the plays are about power how people use 
it and how power uses them in richard ii the king doesnt 
appreciate the power he has until he loses it richard in a 
lyrical galvanizing performance by charles janasz gains spiritual 
strength as he loses control of temporal power 
he stands in contrast to bolingbroke who decisively takes 
control of his life and the crown to become henry iv but once 
king he has little rest from guilt over richards death and 
selfdoubt about his ability stephen yoakam admirably projects 
henrys world weariness the machinations he must go through to 
hold onto the throne 
prince hal also undergoes a transformation as played by barton 
tinapp he goes from roustabout to ruler with remarkable skill 
hes at home with falstaff and the other rowdies at the eastcheap 
tavern but can dismiss them curtly when he is called upon to 
fulfill his royal duty 
steins innovative settings dazzle theres a burnished copper 
design for richard ii a gnarled rustic wooden environment for 
henry iv and then bare exposed rehearsal space for henry v 
with glimpses of the sets from the first two productions as a 
backdrop 
the costumes designed by ann houldward are opulent except 
for one stunning bit of theatricality in henry v in which the 
actors playing the english wear rehearsal clothes the designer 
perhaps took a cue from the opening chorus of henry v which 
entreats the audience to use its imagination in seeing and hearing 
the play 
the three plays were codirected with a fine sense of historical 
pageantry and drama by garland wright the guthries artistic 
director and charles newell a onetime resident director at the 
theater 
garland and i decided early on that the only way we could see 
it work was if both of us were responsible for everything newell 
said in an interview each of us would do all of it 
the idea to do the history play cycle at the guthrie came from a 
plan to have richard iglewski an actor in the company play 
falstaff 
in the winter of 198889 we did a reading of the henry iv 
plays just to listen to them newell said and we realized 
henry iv part 2 had difficulty standing on its own 
then wright had the idea of cradling the two henry iv plays 
between richard ii and henry v 
suddenly it became a very big project said newell it 
was decided the acting company wasnt ready to do that but after 
much thought on garlands part he decided that that very reason 
we werent ready to do it was the reason we should be doing it 
the two directors began informally discussing the plays in july 
1989 in september historians and scholars were brought in to talk 
about the history of the period the manners of the time the 
difference between shakespeares history and actual history 
most helpful were professors of social history newell said 
scholars who could talk about what it was like to live in a 
castle or what was an inn like and who was there and what did 
people eat and drink things that for actors are very useful in 
terms of understanding character 
wright newell and michael lupu the guthries dramaturge 
worked on ways to transform the two henry iv dramas into a 
single work 
we made a decision to try and tell the entire story of what 
both plays were about in one play newell said but we didnt 
want to cut out major sections of the plays as a way to condense 
it rather we wanted to just trim everything that was there and 
somehow compact it 
rehearsals began march 13 nearly three months before the first 
preview performance on june 9 the three shows opened june 30 in an 
allday 12hour marathon 
wright and newell made an unusual decision about those early 
rehearsals the codirectors would do very little talking the first 
month and let the actors find the plays on their own 
we were there to guide and focus but primarily we wanted the 
company to discover the plays themselves as well as to discover 
something about the actual rehearsal process itself newell said 
the actors were encouraged to talk about the scenes they were 
working on it was scary for them because they didnt have a 
single voice or in our case two voices telling them what they 
were going to do newell said 
we had rehearsals in which everybody was in the room at all 
times and anybody could say anything they wanted about the scene 
that we were working on he added suddenly the work became 
about what the company is 
after a month of this work wright and newell split into 
separate rehearsals but they maintained a dialogue with each other 
that allowed them to shape the plays with equal input 
one of the hardest moments was that first day of rehearsal in 
which we were all sitting at tables that had scripts that came off 
the table about 4 or 5 inches newell said the sheer size of 
the project was daunting but like anything that big you just do 
it one step at a time and somehow you get it done 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

