<TEXT>
mo better blues 
the astonishing spike lee surely the most original of new 
filmmakers succeeds where others have stumbled he has made a jazz 
movie that is both authoritative and entertaining 
bertrand taverniers round midnight and clint eastwoods 
bird captured the essence of jazz but were so doggedly 
downbeat that they turned off average audiences 
lees mo better blues has something for everyone comedy 
sex violence drama as well as some of the most sublime jazz to 
be captured on film the rendition of the title tune will haunt us 
for years to come 
gone is the angry attitude of lees last film not that he has 
mellowed out his situations and his dialogue retain plenty of bite 
some may consider his portrayal of the two moneysqueezing 
clubowner brothers as antisemitic 
the prologue is a brief vignette of a new york boy whose mother 
wont let him go out to play until he finishes his trumpet lessons 
the boy grows up to become bleek gilliam denzel washington a 
rising jazz star whose quintet packs the beneath the underdog club 
every night 
bleek tries to balance his career with no help from his 
boyhood friend and manager giant spike lee and romances with a 
wouldbe singer cynda williams and a school teacher joie lee 
bleeks juggling act fails with tragic results 
mo better blues marks denzel washingtons continued 
emergence as a firstrank film actor he is a commanding figure on 
the bandstand and off winner of last years supporting actor 
academy award for glory and twice nominated prior to that 
hes likely to be in the running for lead actor this time 
at over two hours mo better blues could stand trimming 
especially of the bickering scenes that may be unintelligible for 
some ears but lees originality shines through in every scene and 
there is even an unexpected sweetness in the way things are 
resolved 
the film is loaded with powerful performances notably wesley 
snipes as bleeks saxplaying rival the almost continuous score by 
bill lee spikes father adds richness as does ernest dickersons 
burnished photography the brooklyn bridge never looked so good 
the universal pictures release is rated r 
by bob thomas associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
the freshman 
marlon brando is a brilliant actor but lets face it hes not 
known for making audiences laugh heavy dramatic roles are his 
forte the godfather and apocalypse now werent exactly big 
on chuckles 
thats what makes it such a delightful shock to discover in 
the freshman that brando can be funny 
in fact he is the comic heart of the freshman a film so 
hilariously crazy that its plot defies extensive description 
matthew broderick plays a new york university freshman film 
student from vermont whose misadventures in new york lead to a job 
with carmine sabatini the portly sabatini is a little italy 
businessman with an uncanny resemblance to vito corleone of the 
godfather 
this is brando doing a parody of brando and it is so finely 
crafted that it might discourage impersonators from attempting any 
future godfather imitations brando does it better than any of 
his imitators could and he never cracks a smile 
sabatini has the same husky voice the gravelinthemouth 
delivery that makes some of his words incomprehensible and the 
trademark slickeddown hair style and mustache that made corleone a 
part of american film history 
above all he has dignity that extends to a scene in which the 
bulky sabatini is seen majestically ice skating a vision that 
lasts long after the movie 
brandos plot relationship with broderick adds an undertone of 
warmth unexpected in such a broad comedy 
lest we doubt that parody is going on here brodericks 
character clark kellogg attends film classes where the teacher 
a mad professor type played by paul benedict shows film clips 
from the godfather to his enraptured students 
you know the resemblance is incredible broderick whispers 
when he is first introduced to sabatini 
the story of the freshman is pure fantasy broderick is 
commissioned to smuggle a giant lizard known as a komodo dragon 
an endangered species member out of airport customs this lizard 
actually another unendangered species is a star reptile or not 
hes endearing and when bert parks suddenly appears to sing 
there he is your komodo dragon youve got to love this movie 
the lunatic genius behind it all is writerdirector andrew 
bergman who had the inspiration to add bert parks to a movie with 
marlon brando matthew brodrerick and a giant lizard for good 
measure another film great maximilian schell shows up as a 
crazed chef with a thick german accent broderick manages to bring 
sweetness to a role that mostly requires him to look bewildered 
the freshman is an irresistible concoction with fine 
performances from all involved including the lizard but the most 
memorable moments belong to brando this is acting at its finest in 
a film that has no reason to exist except to entertain isnt that 
refreshing 
the tristar picture is rated pg running time 102 minutes 
by linda deutsch associated press writer 
</TEXT>
