<TEXT>
diets and retirement are anathema to 
simone beck master cook and teacher coauthor with julia child of 
mastering the art of french cooking 
with her 86th birthday just past shes looking forward to 
publication of her fifth book next spring it will be an intimate 
autobiography as well as a cookbook 
cooking cant keep you young but it can surely help keep 
fit said beck sitting on the sunny terrace of her provencal 
farmhouse between cannes and grasse crash diets can do you 
little but harm 
it has been 32 years since beck child and louisette bertholle 
published what became the first volume of mastering the art 
the bible of french cuisine for americans yearning to learn the 
secrets of sauces like bechamel bordelaise or hollandaise 
a second volume by beck and child followed with equal success 
while bertholle branched off to write her own cookbooks 
eventually all three were doing their own thing 
after mastering the art beck wrote simcas cuisine in 
1972 her friends call her simca and new recipes in 1979 
although a celebrity in american culinary circles and mentor to 
a couple of generations of american cooks beck is relatively 
unknown in france 
i hope my main statement in life my memoirs and new recipes 
will take off when published by viking next spring said beck 
it doesnt have a title yet but it tells all she said with 
a wink including a bit about my love life also my tricks in 
cooking well known to my pupils but i have new ones up the old 
sleeve 
her new book was inspired by childs encouragement beck said 
when becks husband jean fischbacher died in 1986 child and 
her husband paul who have owned a house on becks property since 
the 1960s came over to give moral support 
child was fascinated by becks life particularly some 
hairraising adventures during world war ii and persuaded her to 
write it down 
its all in the book including how i met julia at a cocktail 
party when i was looking for an american collaborator for a book of 
french recipes beck said 
mastering was an epic effort a labor of love 10 years in 
which beck bertholle and child hashed over french techniques for a 
transatlantic audience 
writing her life story was another challenge it recalls her 
privileged childhood in normandy two marriages and her 
professional life weaving traditional and new menus and recipes 
into the narrative 
id learned food basics in normandy with the family cook 
zulma beck said but when i was a young bride in paris i took 
up bookbinding 
she won a prize and looked around for something more 
interesting after she stumbled onto the cordon bleu school while 
driving around paris in the 1930s she lured the top teacher henri 
pellaprat home to help her prepare fancy dinner parties jotting 
down his tips but she didnt start teaching herself until well 
after world war ii 
during the war id spent much of the time bicycling around 
normandy bargaining with farmers to get food to send to my second 
husband who was in a german prison camp she said 
after the war beck became involved in cooking and teaching at 
lecole des trois gourmandes founded by the coauthors of 
mastering 
later beck taught cooking on her own giving lessons in her 
paris flat at her guest house in southern france and on world 
demonstration tours 
today she teaches less but likes to philosophize on food 
dont talk to me about nouvelle cuisine she said it made 
food attractivelooking for anorexics but thats about all and i 
never could stand eating raw fish an abomination 
and she appreciates her audience in the united states 
i always preferred to write for americans beck said 
french people think they already know everything about cooking 
