<DOCNO> AP900723-0217 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the scene is common older people sitting in 
their equityrich homes struggling to pay the monthly bills for 
many a reverse mortgage also known as a home equity conversion 
may provide relief 
generally reverse mortgages are available to individuals 62 or 
older who owe nothing or very little on their homes 
a homeowner entering into a reverse mortgage receives monthly 
payments from the lender based on several factors including the 
type of mortgage selected age and life expectancy the value of 
the house the predicted value of the house at the end of the loan 
the interest rate and the amount of equity available 
upon death or sale of the home the loan is repaid currently 
there are three basic options from which to choose when selecting a 
reverse mortgage term tenure or line of credit 
under the conditions of a term loan borrowers receive monthly 
payments for a fixed number of years although the loan does not 
have to be repaid until the house is sold or the borrower dies 
interest accrues on the amount received 
since term loans expire after a stated number of years the 
monthly payments received by the borrower usually are larger 
compared with the other options 
term loans generally are best for those who actually plan to 
move at the end of the term thus avoiding additional interest 
charges 
borrowers who choose a tenure mortgage receive monthly payments 
for as long as they live in the home and like a term loan 
repayment is not due until the borrower dies or the house is sold 
however since the exact duration of the loan cannot be determined 
payments normally are less than those paid under a term loan 
agreement 
a line of credit loan allows an individual to borrow against a 
line of credit as needed the lumpsum amount available is based 
on the aforementioned factors and once again need not be rapaid 
until the borrower dies or the house is sold 
in conjunction with any of these loan alternatives borrowers 
may pledge all or a portion of the appreciation on the house to a 
lender increasing the amount of the monthly payments or the line 
of credit 
upon death or sale of the house the borrower or the borrowers 
estate will be responsible for the repayment of the principal 
interest and the agreed upon portion of appreciation 
as with any financing arrangement there are advantages and 
disadvantages associated with a reverse mortgage since a reverse 
mortgage is nothing more than a loan the proceeds are received 
taxfree 
the loans usually are nonrecourse meaning the borrower never 
will be liable for more than the value of the house the biggest 
advantage though for many borrowers is the ability to continue 
living in a house and neighborhood that have become familiar while 
at the same time using the house to increase the quality of life or 
peace of mind 
as for the downside many people do not want to deplete what 
generally is their single most important asset they have worked 
long and hard to pay off the mortgage and collect the deed from the 
bank 
they also may want or feel it is their duty to leave the house 
to their heirs moreover a premature sale of a house due to 
unforeseen circumstances by individuals involved in a shared 
appreciation reverse mortgage may cause them to end up both house 
poor and cash poor borrowers still are liable for property tax and 
insurance costs associated with the house 
lastly because most reverse mortgages are nonrecourse loans 
lenders are reluctant to offer them in response to this 
reluctance however the federal housing administration is 
sponsoring a pilot program that if successful could lead to more 
lenders willing to offer reverse mortgages 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
rebecca godkin is an academic in the tax 
planning division of the college for financial planning 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

