<TEXT>
media spending will grow at a 76 percent yearly 
rate to 4613 billion by 1994 exceeding growth in the economy but 
slowing from its 89 percent pace of the past five years according 
to a new study 
the report from the investment banking firm veronis suhler amp 
associates which specializes in media deals covers spending on 
media ranging from radio and tv to newspapers books magazines 
music and the movies 
in its fourth annual industry forecast released sunday the firm 
said communications industry spending would grow faster than the 
economy from 199094 
the firm expects the economy to grow 72 percent including 
inflation for each of the next five years up from 69 percent in 
the past five 
but it said communications spending will expand more slowly in 
the next five years than in the past five because of maturation 
of the technologydriven industries of the 1980s such as home 
video cable tv compact disc recordings and business information 
broadcasting spending is expected to grow at a 71 percent 
compounded annual rate to 462 billion by 1994 up from 58 
percent for 198489 
network tv advertising spending which rose at a slim 22 
percent annual rate over the past five years as audiences fled to 
