<TEXT>
the nations beekeepers have launched a logo 
campaign they hope will make life sweeter for consumers while 
stinging manufacturers who use only token amounts of honey 
last august the national honey board launched the bear 
facts campaign to authorize manufacturers to use its logo a 
cuddly bear guzzling honey from a jug on products that have honey 
as the primary sweetener 
mary humann acting executive director of the board said the 
campaign has a twofold purpose to help consumers identify 
honeysweetened products quickly by looking for the bear symbol and 
to target products that use the word honey but only contain a 
minute amount or a honey substitute 
each product is tested by a panel of food scientists to make 
sure the boards criteria are met before the logos use is allowed 
more than 55 products from wine to bird food have added the 
logo to their packaging humann said 
we felt that it was a strong addition to our label honey has 
a strong sweetener quality with a lot more positive impact said 
patrick ferrill a spokesman for ralston purina which makes honey 
chex cereal 
the campaign comes at a time when the us food and drug 
administration is researching proposed sweeping changes in food 
labeling one plan would require percentage listings for each 
ingredient which would give consumers a better idea of exactly 
what theyre buying said chris lecos fda press officer in 
washington dc 
stuart greenblatt a spokesman for keebler co in elmhurst 
ill said the honey board campaign is one of several that have 
cropped up recently in the food industry 
everybody is looking for something extra some added value 
he said 
keebler has five products including honey grahams that use 
honey as flavoring but not as the primary sweetener he said 
honey grahams which has been on the grocery store shelves for more 
than a dozen years was named after honey primarily to promote its 
flavor 
gary evans president of sioux honey association in sioux city 
iowa which makes sue bee honey products said apiarists are 
