without using substantial amounts of the sweet gooey substance 
thats why with the national honey boards help we can kind 
of police the industry he said honey is getting to be very 
popular i think some of them are taking advantage of the word 
honey 
ferrill said he didnt know if the logo had gained recognition 
among consumers yet but we hope itll improve the competitive 
edge of our product and thats why we go to the trouble of putting 
it on our product 
the national honey board was authorized by congress and 
established by the agriculture department in 1986 to promote honey 
and honey research beekeepers pay 1 cent per pound of honey to 
fund the board 
