<TEXT>
the united states and the european community on 
monday postponed a showdown over agricultural subsidies as senior 
negotiators launched a new bid to speed the progress of talks aimed 
at a more open global economy 
but officials from washington and brussels made it clear that 
with less than five months remaining in the talks there are still 
vast differences over farm policy 
us deputy trade representative julius katz said the united 
states would continue pressing for elimination of tradedistorting 
export subsidies 
but guy legras senior ec negotiator on agriculture indicated 
the 12nation trading bloc would stand by its defense of export 
assistance to help european farmers compete in world markets 
agriculture is the most contentious of the 15 sectors covered by 
the negotiations sponsored by the general agreement on tariffs and 
trade the talks were launched in uruguay in 1986 and are scheduled 
to end in december with accords to reduce barriers to trade and 
expand rules into new areas worth an estimated 1 trillion 
negotiators from 105 countries in the talks are in geneva for 
the fiveday meeting of the gatts toplevel trade negotiations 
committee to push the ambitious talks and identify the sticking 
points 
arthur dunkel directorgeneral of gatt higlighted textiles and 
services such as banking and aviation as two areas of impasse 
dunkel told a news conference that governments were playing 
cat and mouse in the negotiations by making progress in one 
sector conditional on their demands being met in another area 
but he said there was a possible opening in talks on agriculture 
reform 
this was after an agricultural working group meeting agreed to 
use a compromise proposal on farm policy as to intensify the 
negotiations as agreed by world leaders at the houston economic 
summit earlier this month 
a statement issued by the groups chairman aart de zeeuw said 
negotiations on substantive work would start at the end of august 
the decision averts a crisis at the geneva meeting but merely 
delays the inevitable clash 
the compromise text by de zeeuw focuses on cutting domestic farm 
payments and price supports and converting all import barriers 
into tariffs which will be reduced 
it is toughest on export subsidies and states these should be 
reduced more than other forms of support and protection 
legras said the ecs still was strongly opposed to the proposals 
on export subsidies the ec commission agress there should be 
tightening of export aids but refuses to take firm steps to reduce 
them 
katz insisted subsidy cuts must be a central part of any deal on 
farm policy 
it is not sufficient to have treatment of export subsidies as 
a residual issue the conclusion of the negotiations has to deal 
with export subsidies with specific commitments he said 
current state assistance to farmers costs consumers and 
taxpayers an estimated 245 billion annually 
us president george bush has warned that failure to reach a 
satisfactory agreement on slashing farm supports will cause the 
collapse of the entire uruguay round risking further trade wars 
and protectionism 
the removal of agriculture from the agenda at the tnc meeting 
leaves the 450 negotiators free to concentrate on other problem 
areas 
these include trade in textiles worth some 177 billion in 
1988 trade is currently regulated by the multifiber arrangement 
mfa and not by gatt under this system import quotas are fixed in 
bilateral deals 
washington wants to abolish the mfa and replace it with a global 
quota system with quotas negotiated on a multilateral basis and 
increased over a tenyear period critics say a completely new 
system would enable washington to slip in new restrictions 
there also is stalemate in efforts to set up a general agreement 
on services to help liberalize services trade worth at least 600 
billion annually 
most countries favor an accord covering all sectors but the 
united states wants a narrower framework which would allow it to 
continue bilateral deals which benefit the us aviation and 
shipping industry and offer some control over financial services 
</TEXT>
