a lastminute costcutting agreement reached with 
unions at irish press newspapers paves the way for the 
ingersollmanaged group to restore the titles to a prime position 
in ireland the management said monday 
the group irish press newspapers ltd was founded nearly 60 
years ago by former irish premier and president eamon de valera it 
is 50percent owned by embattled us publisher ralph ingersolls 
british company ingersoll publications ltd 
the group reached the agreement with the national union of 
journalists and the irish print union on sunday just before it was 
to close down the irish press evening press and sunday press 
the settlement calls for 200 voluntary layoffs the immediate 
start of the use of new technology and the introduction of a basic 
5shift 35hour work week throughout the company 
journalists have been working a fourday 28hour week 
the 750 workers had rejected the same proposals on thursday 
we are delighted with the agreements we have reached with the 
irish unions the irish press group has been at the heart of irish 
national life for 60 years said james plugh chief executive of 
londonbased ingersoll publications 
through the use of the latest technology our newspaper 
expertise and the remarkable pool of creative talent in ireland 
the way is now clear for our partners and ourselves to restore the 
irish press titles to their preeminent position in the republic of 
ireland he said 
ingersoll publications which bought a halfstake in the 
newspaper group in december 1989 also manages the newspapers 
the remainder of the company is owned by irish press plc the 
company founded by de valera and now chaired by his grandson eamon 
de valera 
ralph ingersoll hit by his heavy debt load of mostly junk 
bonds and a downturn in the us newspaper industry relinquished 
ownership of his us newspaper company ingersoll publications co 
earlier this month 
the new york investment firm em warburg pincus and co his 
partner for seven years agreed to acquire all the stock in 
ingersolls three american companies which publish daily newspapers 
in new haven conn trenton nj and other cities 
ingersoll closed down his startup daily newspaper the st louis 
sun earlier this year after seven months of publication 
the publisher who has said he believes there are more 
publishing opportunities in europe agreed to acquire warburgs 
50percent interest in the british ingersoll company which also 
